                           </math> and <math>
                              <latex>\Vect{z} = (0,0,1)</latex>
                           </math>.</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
				        <solution.hint>
               <para>
                  <para.body>First look for a vector <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{y}</latex>
                     </math> which is not parallel to <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                     </math>, so that <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                     </math> and <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{y}</latex>
                     </math> are linearly independent.</para.body>
               </para>
            </solution.hint>
				        <solution.hint>
               <para>
                  <para.body>Once you have linearly independent vectors <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                     </math> and <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{y}</latex>
                     </math>, consider using the cross product operation to find a vector which is perpendicular to <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                     </math> and <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{y}</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
